  "text": "Quantitative analysis of HBoV DNA in the respiratory aspirates Absolute quantification of DNA by qPCR revealed that the HBoV viral load in HBoV-positive patients varied very broadly, ranged from ,500 to 1610 9 copies per mL of sample material, with median value of 9912 (figure 1). The median viral load which was found in patients with sole HBoV infection was not higher than those who had co-infection with other respiratory viruses (p = 0.2517). A recent review suggested if serum samples were not available for PCR, and then the probable next best option was the quantitative PCR with a cutoff of .10 4 copies/mL of respiratory tract secretions [CITATION_1] . Several previous studies reported that increased serum HBoV IgM and IgG had been found in most of patients who had high HBoV load (. [CITATION_2] 4 copies/mL) in respiratory tract secretions, which was associated with respiratory symptoms [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Therefore the HBoV-positive samples were divided into 2 non-overlapping populations: one group of 15 samples with a high viral load (.10 4 copies/mL) and one group of 16 samples with a low viral load (,10 4 copies/mL).",
